%N A228850 a(n) is the smallest prime which starts a record-length of "alternating" consecutive prime gaps.
%C A228850 Technically, alternation requires more than 2 values of something, so the first term is a convention this sequence and its description (that follows).
%C A228850 Each prime prime(m) is followed by a sequence of prime gaps A001223(m+k), k>=0. We classify a subsequence of A001223 as "alternating" if consecutive values alternatingly increase and decrease, which means, if the associated subsequence of the second differences A036263 (one term shorter) always switches sign if the index increases by one. The length is the maximum l>=1 such that A036263(m+k)*A036263(m+k+1) <0 for all 0<=k<l-1.
%C A228850 These lengths in A036263 starting at A036263(m) are 1, 1, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 4, 3, 2, 1, 2, 1, 1, 1, 3, 2, 1, 4, 3, 2, 1, 2, 1, 4, 3, 2, 1, 7, 6,... for m >=1. The record lengths of 1, 5, 7,... occur at indices i= 1, 3, 29,.. indicating primes A000040(m) = 2, 5, 109,... as listed in this sequence. (Records are defined by a sequence of strictly increasing lengths, as usual in the OEIS; repetition of a length that was recorded earlier cannot define a new record.)
%C A228850 The associated record lengths in A229056 are one larger than defined above, because they do not measure the length in the second differences (A036263) but the length in the first differences (A001223).
%e A228850 a(2) = 5 and A228851(2)=23 indicates the second record is generated by the primes 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19 and 23, and also the primes 3 and 29 indirectly, with differences 2 < 4 > 2 < 4 > 2 < 4. The preceding difference of 2 (5-3) is not greater than 2 and the following difference of 6 (29-23) is not smaller than 4.
%p A228850 Aruns := proc(P)
%p A228850     option remember;
%p A228850     local p,sdiff,i,snew,q,r ;
%p A228850     p := P ;
%p A228850     q := nextprime(p) ;
%p A228850     r := nextprime(q) ;
%p A228850     sdiff := p+r-2*q ;
%p A228850     if sdiff = 0 then
%p A228850         return 1;
%p A228850     else
%p A228850         for i from 1 do
%p A228850             p := q ;
%p A228850             q := r ;
%p A228850             r := nextprime(q) ;
%p A228850             snew := p+r-2*q ;
%p A228850             if snew*sdiff < 0 then
%p A228850                 sdiff := snew ;
%p A228850             else
%p A228850                 return i ;
%p A228850             end if;
%p A228850         end do:
%p A228850     end if;
%p A228850 end proc:
%p A228850 A228850 := proc()
%p A228850     local r,p,i ;
%p A228850     r := 0 ;
%p A228850     p :=2 ;
%p A228850     for i from 1 do
%p A228850         if Aruns(p) > r then
%p A228850             printf("%d\n",p) ;
%p A228850             r := Aruns(p) ;
%p A228850         end if;
%p A228850         p := nextprime(p) ;
%p A228850     end do:
%p A228850 end proc:
%p A228850 A228850() ; # _R. J. Mathar_, Oct 10 2013
%o A228850 (PARI) alt(p) = {ok = 1; q = nextprime(p+1); da = q - p; p = q; q = nextprime(p+1); db = q - p; dir = sign(db - da); if (dir == 0, return (0)); nb = 2; while (ok, p = q; q = nextprime(p+1); dc = q - p; if (dir < 0, ok = db < dc, ok = db > dc); if (ok, nb ++); dir = sign(dc - db); db = dc;); return (nb);}
%o A228850 lista(nn) = {rec = 0; for (n = 1, nn, new = alt(prime(n)); if (new > rec, rec = new; print1(prime(n), ", "));); } \\ _Michel Marcus_, Sep 21 2013
